Converting a collection of objects to key/value pairs is a common problem.  For example:
- [This Stackoverflow question](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/10416424/underscore-js-create-a-map-out-of-list-of-objects-using-a-key-found-in-the-obje) has 36,000 views
- [This CodeReview.SE question](http://codereview.stackexchange.com/questions/57614/convert-object-array-to-hash-map-using-lodash) has over 50,000 views

The most common solution, which I see _all the time_, looks like this:

```
inputs.reduce(function(returnObj, input) {
  returnObj[keyFunc(input)] = valFunc(input);
  return returnObj;
}, {});
```

There are more succinct options using ES6:

```
inputs.reduce((returnObj, input) => ({ ...returnObj, [keyFunc(input)]: valFunc(input) }), {});
Object.assign(...inputs.map(input => ({[keyFunc(input)]: valFunc(input)})));
```

There are also multiple clean-ish ways to do it using lodash:

```
_.zipObject(inputs.map(keyFunc), inputs.map(valFunc));
_.fromPairs(inputs.map(input => [keyFunc(input), valFunc(input)]));
_.reduce(inputs, (returnObj, input) => _.extend(returnObj, {[keyFunc(input)]: valFunc(input) }));
```

However they are all more mental-effort than necessary.  Given how common this problem is, I think it should have its own function:

```
_.toObject(inputs, keyFunc, valFunc);
```

---

Examples:

```
//Input
[
    { key: '1', val: 'a' },
    { key: '2', val: 'b' },
    { key: '3', val: 'c' }
]

//Desired output
{
    '1': 'a',
    '2': 'b',
    '3': 'c'
}

//Current best solution
_.fromPairs(_.map(input, i => [i.key, i.val]));

//With toObject()
_.toObject(input, i => i.key, i => i.val);
```

